In `checkUpkeep` at line 257: `uint256 availableBalance = IERC20(asset).balanceOf(feeAggregator);`

This checks the balance at `feeAggregator` (which is `s_feeAggregator`). When `feeAggregator == address(this)`, this is `IERC20(asset).balanceOf(address(this))` — the balance of the auction contract itself.

So when `s_feeAggregator == address(this)`:


The contract treats itself as the fee aggregator, reading its own balance as eligible assets. It skips the transfer step since assets are already present, runs the auction with those funds, and leaves any residual in the contract at the end — essentially operating in a self-contained mode without needing external transfers.

The property about transferring residuals to the fee aggregator holds in the normal case where there's an external aggregator, but doesn't apply when the contract is its own aggregator since those assets legitimately stay put for the next cycle.

Now I'm checking whether the `assetOut` transfer at the end of the auction is always handled correctly — the code checks the balance and transfers everything to the designated receiver.

For the remaining asset transfer when there's an external aggregator, it sends the full contract balance, which is correct. When there's no external aggregator, residuals stay in the contract by design, which is also fine since `checkUpkeep` already accounts for that available balance and the auction starts with assets already present.

